<comment datatype='string'>Derrick et al. (2009) suggested that  induction of &lt;i&gt;ogt&lt;/i&gt; by NarL alone in response to external nitrate provides a prophylactic effect against possible genotoxicity arising from nitrate metabolism [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19245365&quot;&gt;Squire09&lt;/a&gt;]. NarL activates the &lt;i&gt;ogt&lt;/i&gt; promoter independently of FNR [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19245365&quot;&gt;Squire09&lt;/a&gt;]. NarL (E273 residue) appears to interact directly with RNA polymerase (&amp;alpha;-CTD) to activate transcription of the &lt;i&gt; ogt&lt;/i&gt;  promoter [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32662815&quot;&gt;Ruanto20&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The &lt;i&gt;ogt&lt;/i&gt; promoter is induced by NarL in response to nitrate ions, without help from FNR [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19245365&quot;&gt;Squire09&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
Based on experiments utilizing a mutant background, it was shown that NarP plays little or no role in the &lt;i&gt;ogt&lt;/i&gt; promoter region [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19245365&quot;&gt;Squire09&lt;/a&gt;].
</comment>
